{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493254","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493254"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:02:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:02:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1267"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1267","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1267"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.69,0.07,0.03,0.09,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1267"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55856"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1267","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1267"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1267"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41402"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"128"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2006"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2033"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11683"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11767"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13609"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16220"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35356"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42268"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55856","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55856"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one-hour history of chest pain, worsened with deep inspiration. The pain is central, dull and he gets some relief when he leans forward. He was well prior to this acute onset of pain. The patient\u0027s health issues include hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus, and hypercholesterolaemia. The physical examination is unremarkable. An electrocardiogram demonstrates non-specific widespread ST elevation. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management approach?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ibuprofen","Conduct CTPA","Enoxaparin","Prednisolone","Nitroglycerin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and ECG findings are suggestive of acute pericarditis. The chest pain is pleuritic in nature, worsened by deep inspiration, and relieved by leaning forward, which are classic features of pericarditis. The ECG shows widespread ST elevation, which is typically seen in pericarditis and differs from the localized ST elevation seen in myocardial infarction (MI).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIbuprofen\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct choice as it is a non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID) that helps reduce inflammation and relieve pain in pericarditis. It is the first-line treatment for acute pericarditis of non-myocardial origin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConduct a CTPA\u003C/strong\u003E (computed tomography pulmonary angiography) is used to diagnose pulmonary embolism (PE). While pleuritic chest pain can be a symptom of PE, the ECG findings are more indicative of pericarditis rather than PE.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnoxaparin\u003C/strong\u003E is an anticoagulant used in the management of acute coronary syndromes and PE. It is not indicated in pericarditis unless there is a concurrent thromboembolic event, which is not suggested by the current presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E is a corticosteroid that may be used in pericarditis if NSAIDs and colchicine are contraindicated or ineffective. However, it is not the first-line treatment due to potential side effects and the risk of recurrence of pericarditis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENitroglycerin\u003C/strong\u003E is used to relieve chest pain in angina and MI by dilating coronary arteries. It is not effective in pericarditis, as the pain is not due to myocardial ischemia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute pericarditis is characterised by pleuritic chest pain, often relieved by leaning forward, and widespread ST elevation on ECG.","Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) like ibuprofen are the first-line treatment for acute pericarditis.","Corticosteroids are reserved for cases where NSAIDs and colchicine are contraindicated or ineffective due to potential side effects."],"references":["Adler Y, Charron P, Imazio M, Badano L, Bar\u00f3n-Esquivias G, Bogaert J, Brucato A, Gueret P, Klingel K, Lionis C, Maisch B, Mayosi B, Pavie A, Ristic AD, Sabat\u00e9 Tenas M, Seferovic P, Swedberg K, Tomkowski W; ESC Scientific Document Group. 2015 ESC Guidelines for the diagnosis and management of pericardial diseases: The Task Force for the Diagnosis and Management of Pericardial Diseases of the European Society of Cardiology (ESC)Endorsed by: The European Association for Cardio-Thoracic Surgery (EACTS). Eur Heart J. 2015 Nov 7;36(42):2921-2964.","Rahman, A., \u0026 Saraswat, A.  Pericarditis. Australian Family Physician, 46(11), 810-814. 2017. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2017/november/pericarditis","Ismail TF. Acute pericarditis: Update on diagnosis and management. Clin Med (Lond). 2020 Jan;20(1):48-51. doi: 10.7861/clinmed.cme.20.1.4. PMID: 31941732; PMCID: PMC6964178."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41402"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1267"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41402"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-18T12:16:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-18T12:17:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1267"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55856"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"http